8. Let a be the original amount of grass on one acre, and let $g$ stand for the amount of grass that grows on one acre in one week. Assume a cow eats e acres per week. Then we can say that the total amount of grass eaten under the first of the two given conditions is: number of cows * amount eaten per week * number of weeks
$$
\begin{array}{r}
3 * \mathrm{e} * 2=2 \mathrm{a}+4 \mathrm{~g} \\
6 \mathrm{e}=2 \mathrm{a}+4 \mathrm{~g}
\end{array}
$$

And the second condition gives:
$$
\begin{aligned}
2 * \mathrm{e} * 4 & =2 \mathrm{a}+4 * 2 \mathrm{~g} \\
8 \mathrm{e} & =2 \mathrm{a}+8 \mathrm{~g}
\end{aligned}
$$

Subtracting the two obtained equations yields $2 \mathrm{e}=4 \mathrm{~g}$, so $\mathrm{e}=2 \mathrm{~g}$.
Plugging back into first equation gives $12 \mathrm{~g}=2 \mathrm{a}+4 \mathrm{~g}$, so $\mathrm{a}=4 \mathrm{~g}$.
Now, the 6-week conditions asks how many cows will eat all the grass on six hectares of land in six weeks, together with all the grass that regrows there over the six weeks?
Let c represent the number of cows:
$$
\begin{aligned}
c * e * 6 & =6 a+6 * 6 g \\
6 e c & =6 a+36 g
\end{aligned}
$$

Plug in $\mathrm{e}=2 \mathrm{~g}$ and $\mathrm{a}=4 \mathrm{~g}$, so $6 * 2 \mathrm{~g} * \mathrm{c}=6 * 4 \mathrm{~g}+36 \mathrm{~g}$
$$
12 \mathrm{cg}=24 \mathrm{~g}+36 \mathrm{~g}=60 \mathrm{~g}
$$

So $12 \mathrm{c}=60$ and $\mathrm{c}=5$.
Answer: 5 cows

